                                                                Learning-to-Rank
(1)....................................................................................................................................................................
What is Learning-to-Rank (LTR) ?
- LTR = ML for ranking search results
- instead of handcrafted formulas learns for data (query-document pairs)

(2)....................................................................................................................................................................
LTR as a Supervised Learning Task
- uses labeled training data:
      - Features: BM25, PageRank, Click-through rate, Recency, etc.
      - Labels: how relevant a document is for a query
Key Components
- Feature extraction : collects ranking signals
- Loss function optimization : learns the best ranking model

(3)....................................................................................................................................................................
Three major LTR Approaches

a. Pointwise LTR : (easy but ignores relative order)
- Treats ranking as a regression/classification problem.
- Predicts individual document scores (like BM25 but learned).
- Examples: Linear Regression, Decision Trees.

b. Pairwise LTR : (captures ranking order better)
- Compares pairs of documents and learns which one should rank higher.
- Examples: RankNet (Neural Network for ranking).

c. Listwise LTR : (most powerful but complex)
- Optimizes the entire ranking list using IR metrics (NDCG, MAP).
- Example: LambdaMART (Gradient Boosted Trees for ranking).

